<br>
For instance, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>as a passenger</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> on 2-lane highway drives, I will refrain from conversing while the driver pulls into the opposing lane to pass a slower-moving car.  I don't resume the conversation until the passing manouvre has been completed and we have resumed a more normal speed.  Someone on the other end of the cell phone can't modify their conversation style like that because they aren't aware of driver's environment or changes in driving conditions.<br>
<br>
Aside from that, people treat general phone conversations differently than in-person conversations.  One is far more conscious of the time-limited nature of a phone call, so one tends to pay more attention to the conversation to avoid wasting what is perceived as &quot;valuable&quot; time.  A passenger in your car isn't able to just hop out the second the conversation is over - they're pretty much with you until you reach your destination, so neither participant feels a need to rush the conversation.  If a sentence or two is missed/ignored due to traffic conditions, both parties understand, and neither takes offense.  Try ignoring every other sentence on a phone call, though - betcha person on the other end will be less than impressed.<br>
<br>
Hands-free or not, phone conversations just don't have the type of flexibility that in-person conversations do.  It's a qualitatively different experience.  While I haven't yet decided if I support a ban on cell phones, I don't think it's reasonable to directly compare using them while driving to having a conversation with a passenger.  The mindsets (of both participants) in the two situations are just too different. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=absolutemaster>Absolute Master</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 299<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/25/03 9:56 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: UK bans drivers from using mobile phones</span><hr size=1> A similar law in Ontario was passed a while ago on the ban on cellphones. Cellphone drivers are dangerous. And while YOU may think that you are paying attention on the road while driving, there are a lot of things you do while on the phone that subconsciously you are not aware you are doing. When you dial, are you really paying attention to what's on the road? What about if you need to write down an important phone number?<br>
<br>
